00:25:32,781 --> 00:25:35,743
Let's say the "A" end is 12:00
and the "B" end is 12:01.

449
00:25:35,868 --> 00:25:38,704
All right? We start the machine
with the weeble at the "A" end.

450
00:25:38,829 --> 00:25:40,914
- It travels forward...
- You got to write this down.

451
00:25:41,040 --> 00:25:43,184
- Aaron, there's nothing to write down.
- I'm writing it down.

452
00:25:43,208 --> 00:25:45,335
Fine, it travels forward
normally towards the "B" end,

453
00:25:45,461 --> 00:25:47,921
and when it gets there,
the feed runs down parabolically

454
00:25:48,047 --> 00:25:51,207
until it should stop, but it doesn't.
It curves back around towards the "A" end.

455
00:25:51,550 --> 00:25:53,870
When it gets back to the "A" end...
Now, curve that around.

456
00:25:53,969 --> 00:25:58,098
OK, now the weeble has experienced
a total of two minutes, and again it curves...

457
00:25:58,223 --> 00:26:00,100
(AARON) Back around. It curves parabolically.

458
00:26:00,225 --> 00:26:03,145
Right. So, it comes back around again,
and it does this about 1,300 times,

459
00:26:03,187 --> 00:26:04,980
and when it finally exits on the "B" end,

460
00:26:05,105 --> 00:26:07,417
it's travelled an odd number
of forward and backward trips.

461
00:26:07,441 --> 00:26:11,070
Now, what is so special about 1,300?
Why is it about 1,300? Why isn't it exact?

462
00:26:11,195 --> 00:26:13,739
- This is not empirical.
- Here, give me that.

463
00:26:13,864 --> 00:26:17,576
I don't know why it's not exact.
There's some sort of probability there.

464
00:26:17,701 --> 00:26:20,496
OK, every time it hits the "B" end
there's a chance, OK?

465
00:26:20,621 --> 00:26:23,123
A small chance it won't
curve back around towards the "A" end.

466
00:26:23,248 --> 00:26:26,293
And for some reason, it takes about
1,300 trips before it finally does.

467
00:26:27,461 --> 00:26:30,464
But it does have to exit, or else we wouldn't
be able to see it afterwards.

468
00:26:30,589 --> 00:26:32,716
OK, let's take a look at this.

469
00:26:33,425 --> 00:26:35,344
Yeah, 22 hours, 14 minutes.

470
00:26:39,681 --> 00:26:41,642
1,334 minutes.

471
00:26:41,767 --> 00:26:43,310
Even.

472
00:26:45,270 --> 00:26:46,396
Enter at the "B" end.

473
00:26:48,857 --> 00:26:50,526
Exit at the "B" end.

474
00:26:53,821 --> 00:26:55,590
(ABE) I just want you to see it
the way I saw it.

475
00:26:55,614 --> 00:26:57,116
I am trying, OK? I really am, here.

476
00:26:57,241 --> 00:26:59,636
Look, everything we're putting in that box
becomes ungrounded.

477
00:26:59,660 --> 00:27:02,621
And I don't mean grounded like to the earth.
I mean, not tethered.

478
00:27:02,746 --> 00:27:05,666
We're blocking whatever keeps them
moving forward, so they flip-flop.

479
00:27:05,791 --> 00:27:08,627
Inside the box, it's like a street,
and both ends are cul-de-sacs.

480
00:27:08,752 --> 00:27:11,004
I mean, this isn't frame dragging
or Wormhole matching.

481
00:27:11,130 --> 00:27:15,050
- This is Basic Mechanics and Heat 101.
- This is not mechanics and heat.

482
00:27:19,680 --> 00:27:21,181
We can publish.

483
00:27:22,057 --> 00:27:25,185
- Yeah, we can publish.
- No, I mean we can really publish.

484
00:27:26,645 --> 00:27:28,981
Aaron, the weeble's stupid.
It can't move.

485
00:27:29,106 --> 00:27:31,483
I mean, even if we were
to put the weeble in at point "B"

486
00:27:31,608 --> 00:27:33,586
it's still just going
to bounce around back and forth,

487
00:27:33,610 --> 00:27:35,821
until it gets kicked out at the "B" end.

488
00:27:40,117 --> 00:27:41,660
But if it were smart...

489
00:27:43,537 --> 00:27:47,457
it could enter at the "B" end
and exit at the "A" end before it flips back.

490
00:27:51,753 --> 00:27:54,173
You're talking about making a bigger one.

491
00:27:54,298 --> 00:27:55,898
You're talking about
making a bigger one.

492
00:27:57,176 --> 00:27:58,677
I... I didn't say anything.

493
00:27:59,261 --> 00:28:01,221
You're the one talking about it.

494
00:28:01,930 --> 00:28:03,891
So, you believe me?

495
00:28:05,642 --> 00:28:07,019
No, I don't.

496
00:28:07,144 --> 00:28:10,480
- Come on. Let's go get a drink or something.
- Yeah.

497
00:28:14,443 --> 00:28:17,446
- (AARON) We're going to have to move it.
- We will.

498
00:28:19,323 --> 00:28:21,563
We need a box big enough
for a person to fit into, right?

499
00:28:21,658 --> 00:28:22,784
As far as turning it on...

500
00:28:22,910 --> 00:28:25,930
(ABE) I was testing the box. It turns out
