but it's not till Saturday.

549
00:33:17,287 --> 00:33:18,723
But even if we win the full $10 million,

550
00:33:18,747 --> 00:33:21,142
it's only a couple of hundred thousand a year
for, what, the next 30 years?

551
00:33:21,166 --> 00:33:22,792
Only.

552
00:33:22,918 --> 00:33:25,670
- And that's just one good trade.
- A couple of days like this.

553
00:33:25,795 --> 00:33:27,756
That was just running a test.
In and out.

554
00:33:27,881 --> 00:33:30,717
OK. Well, I want to do what you did.
OK? Exactly what you did.

555
00:33:30,842 --> 00:33:32,802
(ABE) OK, the first thing I did
is call in sick.

556
00:33:32,928 --> 00:33:35,648
- (AARON) OK, I did that.
- And then I drove to the storage facility.

557
00:33:35,722 --> 00:33:37,766
OK, but I need to drop
Lauren off at school first.

558
00:33:37,891 --> 00:33:40,435
OK, then meet me there.
We're going to need both cars.

559
00:33:40,560 --> 00:33:43,247
But we need to park yours way down
the road, out of sight of the facility.

560
00:33:43,271 --> 00:33:46,608
- Wait, why are we doing that?
- Because we need a ride home.

561
00:33:46,733 --> 00:33:48,443
- What is that...
- No, it'll make sense.

562
00:33:48,568 --> 00:33:50,278
OK, I'll be patient.

563
00:33:51,112 --> 00:33:54,115
When I got to the storage room,
I flooded the box with argon,

564
00:33:54,241 --> 00:33:58,453
and then I had to tighten it up
to secure the leaks.

565
00:33:58,578 --> 00:34:01,081
- There's leaks?
- There's always leaks.

566
00:34:04,876 --> 00:34:09,714
At 8:30am I set the timer for 15 minutes,

567
00:34:09,839 --> 00:34:12,342
I jumped in the car,
and drove to Russelfield.

568
00:34:13,176 --> 00:34:15,637
- OK, I lost it.
- What?

569
00:34:15,762 --> 00:34:16,763
Why the timer?

570
00:34:17,430 --> 00:34:19,599
Because the moment
we start those machines

571
00:34:19,724 --> 00:34:22,352
is the moment we'll end up
getting out of them, and...

572
00:34:22,477 --> 00:34:23,562
Right. Got it. Sorry.

573
00:34:23,687 --> 00:34:25,498
I don't want to be standing around
when they do.

574
00:34:25,522 --> 00:34:26,565
Yep.

575
00:34:27,983 --> 00:34:32,529
(ABE) While I was on the road at 8:45,
the machine kicked on by itself, and...

576
00:34:33,530 --> 00:34:35,949
by 8:49 it was completely warmed up.

577
00:34:44,249 --> 00:34:49,546
In Russelfield I got a hotel room
and tried to isolate myself.

578
00:34:49,671 --> 00:34:51,381
Wait, what do you mean, "isolate"?

579
00:34:51,506 --> 00:34:54,092
I mean, I closed the windows,
I unplugged everything in the room,

580
00:34:54,217 --> 00:34:56,344
the telephone,
TV, clock, radio, everything.

581
00:34:56,469 --> 00:34:59,431
I didn't want to take the chance
of running into someone I knew,

582
00:34:59,556 --> 00:35:01,316
or seeing something
on the news that might...

583
00:35:01,433 --> 00:35:05,895
If we're dealing with causality,
and I don't even know for sure...

584
00:35:06,021 --> 00:35:08,064
- I just..
- What?

585
00:35:08,189 --> 00:35:10,025
Took myself out of the equation.

586
00:35:10,150 --> 00:35:12,569
- (AARON) Err on the side of caution.
- Yes.

587
00:35:13,361 --> 00:35:15,572
Well, then what did you do all clay?

588
00:35:18,992 --> 00:35:21,745
I just sat there.
I mean, I had some books, but...

589
00:35:21,870 --> 00:35:23,055
(AARON) What? Were you nervous?

590
00:35:23,079 --> 00:35:26,333
Yeah. It's just mind-numbing,
all the second-guessing.

591
00:35:31,212 --> 00:35:33,214
Evacipate.

592
00:35:37,802 --> 00:35:41,056
At 2:30pm,
I stopped by Williams Medical Supply,

593
00:35:41,181 --> 00:35:43,516
and picked up a class "E"
oxygen tank and mask.

594
00:35:43,642 --> 00:35:47,145
I called my mutual fund company
and asked which stock in their mid-cap fund

595
00:35:47,270 --> 00:35:49,147
had the greatest percentage gain that day.

596
00:35:49,272 --> 00:35:52,150
The idea was just to get enough information
for one good trade.

597
00:35:52,275 --> 00:35:55,087
(AARON) When we go, can we just download
chart data? Trade on each movement?

598
00:35:55,111 --> 00:35:57,711
Yeah, but if we do that,
I want to use the library in Russelfield,

599
00:35:57,822 --> 00:35:59,658
use their computers.

600
00:36:13,630 --> 00:36:18,593
So, I got to the storage room at about 3:15,
and out off the power to the box.

601
00:36:18,718 --> 00:36:21,721
It cycled down
to a tolerable level at about 3:19.

602
00:36:21,846 --> 00:36:24,325
You see, the trick is to get in
after it reaches a comfortable level,

603
00:36:24,349 --> 00:36:28,269
but before it shuts off completely.
There's a window there.

604
00:36:28,395 --> 00:36:30,230
So, does it hurt?

605
00:36:31,815 --> 00:36:33,692
Yeah. Yeah, it does a little.

606
00:36:33,817 --> 00:36:35,902
It's not bad, though,
if you wait for the right time.

607
00:36:36,027 --> 00:36:39,197
It's like a small static shock.
Once you're in, you're fine, though.

608
00:36:39,322 --> 00:36:40,490
What?

609
00:36:40,615 --> 00:36:43,615
(AARON) I know you've done it, OK?
And I can only assume that you don't have

610
00:36:43,660 --> 00:36:45,745
cancer or male impotence because of it.

611
00:36:45,870 --> 00:36:48,182
But I mean, what is your opinion
on how safe this thing is?

612
00:36:48,206 --> 00:36:50,917
Aaron, I can imagine no way
in which this thing would be considered

613
00:36:51,042 --> 00:36:53,169
anywhere remotely close to safe.

614
00:36:53,294 --> 00:36:56,798
All I know is I spent six hours in there,
and I'm still alive.

615
00:36:59,217 --> 00:37:01,177
You still want to do it?

616
00:37:02,679 --> 00:37:04,723
(METAL THUDDING)

617
00:37:12,272 --> 00:37:14,190
(MACHINE HUMMING)

618
00:37:18,278 --> 00:37:21,281
I set the alarm on my stopwatch
for six hours.

619
00:37:21,406 --> 00:37:25,577
I regulated the O2 tank,
took some Dramamine and tried to sleep.

620
00:37:25,702 --> 00:37:26,745
Did you?

621
00:37:27,370 --> 00:37:29,539
- What?
- Did you sleep?

622
00:37:29,664 --> 00:37:31,040
Not at first.

623
00:37:31,166 --> 00:37:33,501
You know, I've never considered
myself claustrophobic,

624
00:37:33,626 --> 00:37:37,547
but I started sweating and I couldn't find
the right flow rate on the tank,

625
00:37:37,672 --> 00:37:40,091
and I was breathing a lot differently

626
00:37:40,216 --> 00:37:42,552
than I was when I was testing it
on the outside.

627
00:37:42,677 --> 00:37:45,138
Eventually, I settled down, and...

628
00:37:45,263 --> 00:37:47,303
I don't know,
maybe it was the Dramamine kicking in,

629
00:37:47,390 --> 00:37:50,101
but I remember this moment in there,
in the dark,

630
00:37:50,226 --> 00:37:52,771
with the reverberation of the machine.

631
00:37:52,896 --> 00:37:55,940
It was maybe the most content
I've ever been.

632
00:37:58,610 --> 00:38:02,739
I woke up on my own without the alarm
and waited for the machine to cool down.

633
00:38:02,864 --> 00:38:04,991
Cool down from my perspective.

634
00:38:05,116 --> 00:38:07,660
It got to a point
where it sounded safe to get out

635
00:38:07,786 --> 00:38:09,472
but the stopwatch still showed
a couple minutes

636
00:38:09,496 --> 00:38:12,540
so I trusted the math and waited.

637
00:38:42,612 --> 00:38:44,239
(METAL THUDDING)

638
00:38:46,241 --> 00:38:48,451
(AARON SHIVERING)

