00:53:58,110 --> 00:53:59,963
do they both ring at the same time,
or is there...

898
00:53:59,987 --> 00:54:02,340
- That's not how they work.
- They both ring. It's a radio signal.

899
00:54:02,364 --> 00:54:04,074
No, it's a network.

900
00:54:04,199 --> 00:54:07,039
The network checks each area.
When it finds the phone, it stops ringing.

901
00:54:07,119 --> 00:54:09,204
It only... It rings the first one.

902
00:54:11,081 --> 00:54:12,791
This one's ringing.

903
00:54:12,916 --> 00:54:14,084
Right.

904
00:54:14,209 --> 00:54:16,209
So the one your double has
in Russelfield can't be.

905
00:54:16,253 --> 00:54:17,796
Right. I think we broke symmetry.

906
00:54:19,923 --> 00:54:23,886
- Are you sure that's how cell phones work?
- No.

907
00:54:24,595 --> 00:54:25,679
You feel all right?

908
00:54:27,431 --> 00:54:30,142
- I feel fine. Do you?
- Yeah.

909
00:54:44,031 --> 00:54:46,158
(CAR ALARM BLARING)

910
00:54:46,950 --> 00:54:48,202
(CAR HORN HONKING)

911
00:54:58,796 --> 00:55:01,590
- (ABE) Is Kara asleep? Did I wake you up?
- Yeah.

912
00:55:01,715 --> 00:55:05,344
No, not me,
it felt more like a nap.

913
00:55:05,469 --> 00:55:07,638
I think my body's getting used
to these 36-hour days.

914
00:55:07,763 --> 00:55:08,847
What's going on?

915
00:55:08,972 --> 00:55:13,060
We can do this, but we have to do it now.
Do you have his home address?

916
00:55:13,185 --> 00:55:14,394
Why now?

917
00:55:14,520 --> 00:55:17,564
We were planning on taking a trip tomorrow,
right? Just like today?

918
00:55:17,689 --> 00:55:20,275
- Yeah, for stocks.
- OK, well...

919
00:55:20,400 --> 00:55:23,445
Half an hour ago I was asleep.
This car alarm woke me up.

920
00:55:23,570 --> 00:55:26,090
These kids were down skating by,
hitting every car on the block.

921
00:55:26,114 --> 00:55:30,160
So we go right now, do our business
at the Platts', get back in the box,

922
00:55:30,285 --> 00:55:32,931
and come back to right before
those kids are setting off the alarms.

923
00:55:32,955 --> 00:55:36,750
All we'd really have to do is stand there
in plain sight to scare them off.

924
00:55:36,875 --> 00:55:38,715
So that way my double
sleeps through the night,

925
00:55:38,794 --> 00:55:40,838
they don't have
the conversation we're having now,

926
00:55:40,963 --> 00:55:42,756
and they get in the box tomorrow as usual.

927
00:55:44,341 --> 00:55:48,679
- Yeah. They'll be changed. But...
- Yeah, but at least they'll get in the box.

928
00:55:51,056 --> 00:55:54,560
Wait, how do we go back that far
if the machines haven't been running?

929
00:55:57,312 --> 00:55:58,605
Have they been running?

930
00:56:00,148 --> 00:56:04,069
Yeah. I started going by at five o'clock
and turning them on, 5:00pm.

931
00:56:05,237 --> 00:56:07,257
I just got tired of the whole
unanswerable question...

932
00:56:07,281 --> 00:56:10,284
Are we doing this as an experiment,
or are we doing this for me?

933
00:56:10,409 --> 00:56:12,452
- A little of both.
- Five o'clock.

934
00:56:13,161 --> 00:56:16,832
If we get this done by 3:00,
that's ten hours in the box.

935
00:56:18,083 --> 00:56:19,403
I've got the O2 tanks in the car.

936
00:56:21,336 --> 00:56:23,005
It's going to be a long day.

937
00:56:35,726 --> 00:56:38,770
- Is that...
- Is that Rachel's car?

938
00:56:40,063 --> 00:56:43,483
No, that's not Rachel's, that's her dad's.
They have the same kind.

939
00:56:43,609 --> 00:56:44,818
Did you see that?

940
00:56:45,986 --> 00:56:49,489
That's Mr... That's Mr Granger.
That's Thomas. He's sitting in that car.

941
00:56:49,615 --> 00:56:50,949
What?

942
00:56:51,700 --> 00:56:53,785
I swear that was him.
What the hell is he doing...

943
00:56:53,911 --> 00:56:56,830
just sitting outside my house
at 2:00 in the morning?

944
00:56:58,123 --> 00:57:01,043
I don't believe this.
What, is he following us?

945
00:57:01,168 --> 00:57:02,252
Abe, what are you doing?

946
00:57:02,377 --> 00:57:04,063
- What are you doing?
- Let's just see what he wants.

947
00:57:04,087 --> 00:57:05,773
No, let's just get out
of my neighbourhood first.

948
00:57:05,797 --> 00:57:07,174
- But why?
- Come on.

949
00:57:07,299 --> 00:57:09,635
- Did you see him today?
- No.

950
00:57:11,595 --> 00:57:15,432
I did. I saw him this afternoon.
Around 6:00.

951
00:57:16,183 --> 00:57:18,101
You sure you didn't see him
when we drove past?

952
00:57:18,226 --> 00:57:19,811
No, what?

953
00:57:19,937 --> 00:57:22,957
I'm almost positive this afternoon
he was clean-shaven. In fact, I know he was.

954
00:57:22,981 --> 00:57:25,442
He was ready to go to some function
with his wife.

955
00:57:25,567 --> 00:57:28,028
He looks like he's got, like,
a two or three-day growth now.

956
00:57:28,153 --> 00:57:30,530
- Are you sure?
- No, I'm not sure, but I think so.

957
00:57:36,244 --> 00:57:38,956
Hey, Rachel. Hey, this is Abe.
Did I wake you up?

958
00:57:40,332 --> 00:57:44,169
Yeah, hey, can I get your dad's number
from you real quick?

959
00:57:44,294 --> 00:57:46,505
Yeah. OK, go ahead.

960
00:57:48,632 --> 00:57:51,843
- All right, yeah, thanks.
- Wait, what's he doing?

961
00:57:51,969 --> 00:57:53,929
He's just sitting there.

962
00:57:54,054 --> 00:57:57,307
He got out for a second and I don't know,
I thought he was coming over,

963
00:57:57,432 --> 00:58:00,519
and then he got back in the car.
I think he's drunk.

964
00:58:01,436 --> 00:58:04,356
Hi. Sorry to call so late.

965
00:58:04,481 --> 00:58:07,609
May I speak to Thomas Granger,
please?

966
00:58:08,527 --> 00:58:12,239
Yeah, this is James Miller
from Putney and Myers.

967
00:58:13,156 --> 00:58:14,408
Hi, Mr Granger?

968
00:58:15,909 --> 00:58:16,994
Thomas Granger?

969
00:58:20,914 --> 00:58:23,750
Hey! Hey! What are you doing here?
Come here!

970
00:58:30,716 --> 00:58:32,384
(DOG BARKING)

971
00:58:39,474 --> 00:58:40,809
What happened?

972
00:58:41,935 --> 00:58:43,729
I'm OK. I slipped.

973
00:58:53,280 --> 00:58:54,698
(DOOR OPENING)

974
00:58:54,823 --> 00:58:57,885
I just want to know what box he used.
You built one for you, right? Just the one?

975
00:58:57,909 --> 00:58:59,327
Yeah. How many do you think I made?

976
00:59:03,874 --> 00:59:07,210
And these are set right.
I turned them on at 5:00.

977
00:59:07,335 --> 00:59:09,838
He could have used one
and gone back to 5:00.

978
00:59:09,963 --> 00:59:11,965
He could be in one of them right now.

979
00:59:15,469 --> 00:59:18,138
I say we shut them off
and see if he's in there.

980
00:59:19,431 --> 00:59:21,058
Were you planning on talking to him?

981
00:59:21,183 --> 00:59:23,703
Just tell me if you were.
I'm not going to be mad, just tell me.

982
00:59:23,769 --> 00:59:26,688
No, I promise you. You know I wouldn't.
Are you sure you wouldn't?

983
00:59:26,813 --> 00:59:29,274
You're the one that can't get near
without passing out.

984
00:59:31,860 --> 00:59:34,488
There is no way
I would tell anyone about this. No way.

985
00:59:35,197 --> 00:59:37,133
- Can you think of any reason you might?
- No, I can't.

986
00:59:37,157 --> 00:59:39,427
Sometimes we do things,
but don't know how we got to that point.

987
00:59:39,451 --> 00:59:41,244
- No, I can't.
- Can't what?

988
00:59:41,369 --> 00:59:43,538
I can't think of any reason why I would.

989
00:59:45,373 --> 00:59:46,583
I can't either.

990
00:59:47,793 --> 00:59:49,628
What if it was an emergency?

991
00:59:50,879 --> 00:59:54,279
- So you'd do it if it was an emergency?
- No, I don't know. What, so you might, then?

992
00:59:56,176 --> 00:59:58,595
I don't know.
What kind of emergency?

993
00:59:59,888 --> 01:00:02,224
<i>(MAN) The permutations were endless.</i>

994
01:00:02,349 --> 01:00:04,434
- (PHONE RINGS)
- OK, go ahead.

995
01:00:04,559 --> 01:00:06,186
<i>They tried again going to the source,</i>

996
01:00:06,311 --> 01:00:08,372
<i>but even while keeping him separated
from Abe by two rooms...</i>

997
01:00:08,396 --> 01:00:09,606
Ask him his name.

998
01:00:09,731 --> 01:00:12,210
<i>...Thomas Granger's condition
could only be described as vegetative.</i>

999
01:00:12,234 --> 01:00:13,819
What did he say?

1000
01:00:14,486 --> 01:00:17,030
<i>From this they deduced
that the problem was recursive,</i>

1001
01:00:17,155 --> 01:00:20,492
<i>but beyond that, found themselves admitting,
against their own nature,</i>

1002
01:00:20,617 --> 01:00:23,078
<i>and once again,
that the answer was unknowable.</i>

1003
01:00:23,203 --> 01:00:24,579
What do you think he changed?

1004
01:00:24,704 --> 01:00:26,974
It couldn't have been much.
We didn't have any contact with him

1005
01:00:26,998 --> 01:00:28,726
in the three hours
he could've done anything.

1006
01:00:28,750 --> 01:00:30,210
I know he changed this.

1007
01:00:30,335 --> 01:00:32,814
I know we weren't having
this conversation the first time through.

1008
01:00:32,838 --> 01:00:35,841
- So you don't know what we lost.
- Really, it could not have been much.

1009
01:00:35,966 --> 01:00:38,552
It doesn't matter how much.
It just matters that it's changed.

1010
01:00:38,677 --> 01:00:41,322
- Look, Abe, I know what you're saying, OK?
<i>- (MAN) The question should have been</i>

1011
01:00:41,346 --> 01:00:43,546
<i>what to do with the comatose man
in the guest bedroom.</i>

1012
01:00:43,598 --> 01:00:44,641
We can wait this out.

1013
01:00:44,766 --> 01:00:48,270
<i>But in Abe's mind,
he was already compiling the list.</i>

1014
01:00:53,984 --> 01:00:56,903
<i>Two milligrams of oral triazolam
every seven hours</i>

1015
01:00:57,028 --> 01:01:00,574
<i>induces a safe sleep state
and a minimal metabolic rate.</i>

1016
01:01:02,367 --> 01:01:03,869
<i>At this continued state of rest,</i>

1017
01:01:03,994 --> 01:01:06,705
<i>the human body breathes
0.3 litres of oxygen a minute,</i>

1018
01:01:06,830 --> 01:01:10,041
<i>or roughly 2,000 litres in four days.</i>

1019
01:01:10,167 --> 01:01:14,296
<i>A class E oxygen tank holds 625 litres.</i>

1020
01:01:14,421 --> 01:01:15,964
<i>To maintain hydration,</i>

1021
01:01:16,089 --> 01:01:20,427
<i>the body cycles through a minimum
of two-and-a-half litres of water per day.</i>

1022
01:01:20,552 --> 01:01:22,637
<i>Any food would be a luxury,</i>

1023
01:01:22,762 --> 01:01:25,432
<i>but the small tank
of medical-grade nitrous oxide</i>

1024
01:01:25,557 --> 01:01:28,059
<i>would be needed on the other side.</i>

1025
01:01:28,185 --> 01:01:31,396
<i>Past the room that contained their machines,
and up two levels,</i>

1026
01:01:31,521 --> 01:01:33,398
<i>he made his way to another room</i>

1027
01:01:33,523 --> 01:01:35,817
<i>where he had stored
what I will refer to from here on</i>

1028
01:01:35,942 --> 01:01:38,028
<i>as the failsafe machine.</i>

1029
01:02:11,436 --> 01:02:13,396
(GAS HISSING)

1030
01:03:19,254 --> 01:03:21,840
There he is.
I've been calling you all morning.

1031
01:03:23,508 --> 01:03:24,551
Really?

1032
01:03:25,552 --> 01:03:27,137
Your cell and work.

1033
01:03:32,809 --> 01:03:34,769
- I'm not there.
- Really?

1034
01:03:40,400 --> 01:03:42,152
I don't even know. What?

1035
01:03:44,612 --> 01:03:46,072
I'm just tired.

1036
01:03:46,197 --> 01:03:49,701
I hope you're not implying
that any day is unimportant at Cortex Semi.

1037
01:04:03,381 --> 01:04:05,067
<i>(ABE) I was going to come
give you this big speech</i>

1038
01:04:05,091 --> 01:04:09,346
<i>about how we've been friends for a long time
and built up trust, and that whole thing.</i>

1039
01:04:09,471 --> 01:04:10,764
<i>But how about this instead?</i>

1040
01:04:10,889 --> 01:04:15,518
<i>If you ditch work this afternoon and promise
to do the few small things that I ask you,</i>

1041
01:04:15,643 --> 01:04:18,313
<i>I will in return show you
the most important thing</i>

1042
01:04:18,438 --> 01:04:20,482
<i>that any living organism
has ever witnessed.</i>

1043
01:04:22,609 --> 01:04:26,738
<i>(MAN) At this point there would
have been some discussion.</i>

1044
01:04:29,240 --> 01:04:32,285
<i>Abe would, of course,
want to know how.</i>

1045
01:04:34,496 --> 01:04:37,624
<i>Aaron would have to explain
all about the storage manifest</i>

1046
01:04:37,749 --> 01:04:41,086
<i>and how it showed two rooms
under the name Abram Terger.</i>

1047
01:04:41,795 --> 01:04:44,923
<i>Then Abe would need to know how.</i>

1048
01:04:46,216 --> 01:04:48,343
<i>Aaron would explain
that when he went up there</i>

1049
01:04:48,468 --> 01:04:50,428
<i>and found the failsafe running,</i>

1050
01:04:50,553 --> 01:04:52,347
<i>he knew exactly what it was.</i>

1051
01:04:53,848 --> 01:04:56,726
<i>But Abe would ask, "How?"</i>

1052
01:04:56,851 --> 01:04:59,813
<i>And then the bit
about the modular design of the coffins,</i>

1053
01:04:59,938 --> 01:05:02,738
<i>and how it meant he could fold one up
and take it back inside another.</i>

1054
01:05:04,109 --> 01:05:08,446
<i>They are not one-time use only.
They are recyclable, Aaron would say.</i>

1055
01:05:14,786 --> 01:05:16,413
<i>"How?" Abe would ask.</i>

1056
01:05:19,749 --> 01:05:22,210
<i>And Aaron would describe
how simple things become</i>

1057
01:05:23,461 --> 01:05:26,089
<i>when you know precisely
what someone will have for breakfast</i>

1058
01:05:26,756 --> 01:05:28,842
<i>even in a world of tamper-proof lids.</i>

1059
01:05:51,823 --> 01:05:53,199
<i>How?</i>

1060
01:05:54,367 --> 01:05:56,703
<i>And that's where
I would have entered the story.</i>

1061
01:05:56,828 --> 01:05:58,872
<i>Or exited, depending on your reference.</i>

1062
01:06:01,666 --> 01:06:05,420
<i>Because when Aaron came back
the second time, it wasn't so easy.</i>

1063
01:06:07,547 --> 01:06:09,883
<i>He wasn't expecting me
to put up a fight,</i>

1064
01:06:10,008 --> 01:06:12,969
<i>and by that time
he was too exhausted to take me.</i>

1065
01:06:14,721 --> 01:06:17,974
<i>But for reasons
that are only evident to me now,</i>

1066
01:06:18,099 --> 01:06:22,812
<i>I understood that he simply wanted it more.
That he just had more invested.</i>

1067
01:06:22,937 --> 01:06:24,564
<i>So I left.</i>

1068
01:06:24,689 --> 01:06:27,775
<i>He had already performed the task,
as I had intended to,</i>

1069
01:06:27,901 --> 01:06:31,404
<i>of recording the conversations of the day,
just in case.</i>

1070
01:06:31,529 --> 01:06:34,491
<i>Through that earpiece
he had a three-second lead on the world.</i>

1071
01:06:34,616 --> 01:06:37,452
Aaron, you need some sleep.
Some real sleep.

1072
01:06:38,244 --> 01:06:40,705
I can't. I've got a schedule.

1073
01:06:42,540 --> 01:06:45,001
<i>He had but to speak aloud the words
that came into his head,</i>

1074
01:06:46,044 --> 01:06:47,837
<i>and those around him would fall in line.</i>

1075
01:07:08,900 --> 01:07:10,443
<i>(AARON ON EARPIECE) This is track 3.</i>

1076
01:07:10,568 --> 01:07:13,988
<i>Abe is bringing my car around
and I'm on my way to the court.</i>

1077
01:07:14,113 --> 01:07:15,323
<i>I'll see Will there.</i>

1078
01:07:15,448 --> 01:07:18,660
<i>I'll invite him to the party and make sure
he's bringing Rachel's boyfriend.</i>

1079
01:07:19,994 --> 01:07:21,829
<i>- 'Hey, Will.'
- 'Hey.</i>

1080
01:07:21,955 --> 01:07:24,207
- (AARON) Will, hey.
<i>- (WILL) You pretentious prick!</i>

1081
01:07:24,332 --> 01:07:27,085
You pretentious prick.
What the hell is that? Your cell phone?

1082
01:07:27,210 --> 01:07:29,504
- No, it's a radio.
<i>- 'You look like secret service.</i>

1083
01:07:29,629 --> 01:07:32,924
- You look like secret service.
- Ariel meeting is moved to Wednesday.

1084
01:07:33,049 --> 01:07:35,176
What? What the hell
am I hanging around here for?

1085
01:07:35,301 --> 01:07:38,888
- Yeah, I know. I'm sorry.
<i>- (WILL) Nice shot, Aaron.</i>

1086
01:07:40,890 --> 01:07:43,685
Prick. That is ugly, Aaron.

1087
01:07:43,810 --> 01:07:45,746
<i>(WILL) We could have used
that last week against TI.</i>

1088
01:07:45,770 --> 01:07:47,289
(WILL) At least you've got
your golf game, right?

1089
01:07:47,313 --> 01:07:48,541
<i>I see you've been practising.</i>

1090
01:07:48,565 --> 01:07:51,252
You come out here with your $3-tie
and think you can play white ball.

1091
01:07:51,276 --> 01:07:53,754
- Don't worry, I'm not going to tell anyone.
<i>- (AARON) What are you doing tonight?</i>

1092
01:07:53,778 --> 01:07:55,488
Hey. What are you doing tonight?

1093
01:07:55,613 --> 01:07:57,633
I was supposed to be in Raleigh,
but thanks to you guys I missed my flight.

1094
01:07:57,657 --> 01:07:59,242
- You know Robert?
- Yeah.

1095
01:07:59,367 --> 01:08:01,744
He's got a birthday tonight.
Why don't you come out?

1096
01:08:01,869 --> 01:08:05,873
- I'm just going to hang out with my cousin.
- Bring him. Rachel will be there.

1097
01:08:05,999 --> 01:08:07,834
- Oh, big reunion.
- Exactly.

1098
01:08:07,959 --> 01:08:09,669
That should be fun.

1099
01:08:24,350 --> 01:08:26,185
I don't think I'm doing this.

1100
01:08:28,354 --> 01:08:29,689
Why not?

1101
01:08:31,149 --> 01:08:33,586
Because I can think of about a million
different ways that this can happen

1102
01:08:33,610 --> 01:08:35,820
and nobody comes anywhere near
getting hurt.

1103
01:08:35,945 --> 01:08:38,197
I can call her and see
if she wants to do something else

1104
01:08:38,323 --> 01:08:41,468
or better yet, not even talk to her at all,
and she won't even know about the party.

1105
01:08:41,492 --> 01:08:43,252
That's good for tonight.
What about tomorrow?

1106
01:08:43,328 --> 01:08:45,788
- And every other day?
- I'll take care of tomorrow, tomorrow.

1107
01:08:45,913 --> 01:08:47,373
Yeah, you'll watch her all the time.

1108
01:08:47,498 --> 01:08:49,917
This guy is crazy enough
to walk into a roomful of people

1109
01:08:50,043 --> 01:08:51,210
waving a shotgun around.

1110
01:08:51,336 --> 01:08:53,776
What do you think he's going to do
if he ever finds her alone?

1111
01:08:53,880 --> 01:08:57,383
This way we know exactly what happens.
We have complete control over it.

1112
01:08:57,508 --> 01:09:00,595
At the end of the night,
this guy is arrested and goes to jail.

1113
01:09:00,720 --> 01:09:03,306
That's the way it goes.
Your words, not mine.

1114
01:09:03,890 --> 01:09:05,266
Now come on. It has to be you.

1115
01:09:05,391 --> 01:09:08,186
She said she was there because
you told her you would be there.

1116
01:09:14,525 --> 01:09:17,528
Don't tell me I came back
and did this for nothing.

1117
01:09:21,741 --> 01:09:23,076
He doesn't fire?

1118
01:09:24,619 --> 01:09:26,829
- No. He didn't fire.
- Not even when you rushed him?

1119
01:09:26,954 --> 01:09:28,474
No, he didn't the time I wasn't there.

1120
01:09:28,498 --> 01:09:31,668
He didn't the time I was,
when I rushed him.

1121
01:09:31,793 --> 01:09:33,937
And from what Robert tells you,
he didn't do it tonight.

1122
01:09:33,961 --> 01:09:36,756
He doesn't have the nerve. I mean the guy...
We know everything.

1123
01:09:36,881 --> 01:09:38,925
OK? We're prescient.

1124
01:09:45,390 --> 01:09:46,766
We can still be careful.

1125
01:09:46,891 --> 01:09:48,771
Maybe we can get to the gun
without him knowing.

1126
01:09:49,936 --> 01:09:53,231
We definitely can.
He leaves it in the truck before he goes in.

1127
01:09:53,356 --> 01:09:56,192
I mean, we don't even need to,
but if it makes you feel better...

1128
01:09:56,317 --> 01:09:57,610
What's wrong with our hands?

1129
01:10:00,738 --> 01:10:02,407
What do you mean?

1130
01:10:02,532 --> 01:10:04,659
Why can't we write like normal people?

1131
01:10:07,286 --> 01:10:10,289
I don't know.
I can see the letters.

1132
01:10:11,874 --> 01:10:16,462
I know what they should look like.
I just can't get my hand to make them easily.

1133
01:10:17,380 --> 01:10:19,757
Try comparing it to your left hand.
That looks the same.

1134
01:10:19,882 --> 01:10:21,342
(PHONE RINGING)

1135
01:10:30,059 --> 01:10:31,561
Hey, Rachel.

1136
01:10:35,064 --> 01:10:36,733
Yeah, yeah.

1137
01:10:40,486 --> 01:10:43,114
Hey, guess what today is?

1138
01:10:44,907 --> 01:10:46,701
No, no.
It's your friend Robert's birthday.

1139
01:10:48,995 --> 01:10:51,831
He says he likes records,
so I got him "The Best of Bread".

1140
01:10:51,956 --> 01:10:53,833
No, no, real records, like vinyl.

1141
01:10:53,958 --> 01:10:58,171
<i>(MAN) I can tell you with certainty
what I did that night when it was my turn.</i>

1142
01:10:59,172 --> 01:11:03,092
<i>But I think it would do little good,
because what the world remembers</i>

1143
01:11:03,217 --> 01:11:06,804
<i>the actuality, the last revision,
is what counts, apparently.</i>

1144
01:11:08,306 --> 01:11:10,558
<i>So how many times did it take Aaron</i>

1145
01:11:10,683 --> 01:11:13,311
<i>as he cycled through
the same conversations</i>

1146
01:11:13,436 --> 01:11:16,147
<i>lip-synching trivia over and over?</i>

1147
01:11:16,272 --> 01:11:19,567
<i>How many times would it take
before he got it right?</i>

1148
01:11:19,692 --> 01:11:21,486
<i>Three? Four?</i>

1149
01:11:22,737 --> 01:11:24,113
<i>Twenty?</i>

1150
01:11:25,072 --> 01:11:28,326
<i>I've decided to believe that only one more
would have done it.</i>

1151
01:11:28,451 --> 01:11:31,370
<i>I can almost sleep at night
if there's only one more.</i>

1152
01:11:32,371 --> 01:11:36,667
<i>Slowly and methodically
he reverse-engineered a perfect moment.</i>

1153
01:11:38,836 --> 01:11:42,882
<i>He took from his surroundings what
was needed and made of it something more.</i>

1154
01:11:56,229 --> 01:11:59,482
<i>And once the details
had been successfully navigated,</i>

1155
01:11:59,607 --> 01:12:02,610
<i>there would be nothing left to do
but wait for the conflict.</i>

1156
01:12:07,448 --> 01:12:10,117
<i>Maybe the obligatory
last-minute moral debate</i>

1157
01:12:10,243 --> 01:12:13,037
<i>until the noise of the room
escalates into panic</i>

1158
01:12:13,162 --> 01:12:16,207
<i>and background screams
as the gunman walks in.</i>

1159
01:12:17,875 --> 01:12:21,629
<i>And eventually he must have got it perfect,
and it must have been beautiful</i>

1160
01:12:21,754 --> 01:12:24,590
<i>with all the praise and adoration
he had coming.</i>

1161
01:12:24,715 --> 01:12:27,134
<i>He had probably saved lives, after all.</i>

1162
01:12:29,053 --> 01:12:32,181
<i>Who knows what would have happened
if he hadn't been there?</i>

1163
01:12:44,443 --> 01:12:45,862
(AARON) Look...

1164
01:12:47,154 --> 01:12:49,490
I know that things are bad, OK?

1165
01:12:51,367 --> 01:12:54,787
I know that you don't agree
with what I've done.

1166
01:12:54,912 --> 01:12:55,913
I know that you're upset,

1167
01:12:56,038 --> 01:12:58,708
and to be honest I'm not too happy
with you, either, right now.

1168
01:13:00,334 --> 01:13:03,254
But you know that this is going to pass.
So let's just go.

1169
01:13:03,379 --> 01:13:06,275
Let's get out there. Let's go somewhere
where we don't speak the language.

1170
01:13:06,299 --> 01:13:08,593
Aaron, we don't have
the money back here

1171
01:13:08,718 --> 01:13:10,344
and we'd have to steal
our own passports.

1172
01:13:10,469 --> 01:13:12,305
Money? We'll make money.

1173
01:13:12,930 --> 01:13:14,850
They have sports betting in Vegas.
March madness?

1174
01:13:14,932 --> 01:13:17,643
We'll make enough in one night
to finance a thousand vacations.

1175
01:13:17,768 --> 01:13:20,605
- Passports.
- You know they're not using theirs anyways.

1176
01:13:20,730 --> 01:13:21,814
(BANGING)

1177
01:13:21,939 --> 01:13:25,276
Now, come on. I'm thinking Star City.
Check out the cosmonaut training grounds.

1178
01:13:25,401 --> 01:13:26,402
(BANGING ON DOOR)

1179
01:13:26,527 --> 01:13:28,029
I'm staying here.

1180
01:13:29,071 --> 01:13:30,406
Why?

1181
01:13:30,531 --> 01:13:32,700
(BANGING CONTINUES)

1182
01:13:40,625 --> 01:13:42,853
(AARON) They'll be building
their own boxes in another day.

1183
01:13:42,877 --> 01:13:45,171
And yours already knows
what they've built.

1184
01:13:45,296 --> 01:13:47,465
You're not going to be able
to watch them forever.

1185
01:13:49,550 --> 01:13:51,260
(ABE) The box Abe is building
won't work.

1186
01:13:52,428 --> 01:13:53,971
He's got it wired wrong.

1187
01:13:54,680 --> 01:13:58,476
And if they fix that,
I'll start actually taking pieces out of it.

1188
01:13:58,601 --> 01:14:00,895
It's just a gimmick.
It doesn't work anymore.

1189
01:14:01,020 --> 01:14:03,498
And your double will say
they have to move on to something else.

1190
01:14:03,522 --> 01:14:07,485
- And mine will agree. They're friends.
- You're staying? Why?

1191
01:14:07,610 --> 01:14:09,695
Why? Let's see,
why would Abe stay?

1192
01:14:09,820 --> 01:14:12,490
What possible reason
could there be to be here?

1193
01:14:14,825 --> 01:14:18,412
I guess that it just won't
go back far enough, will it?

1194
01:14:20,039 --> 01:14:22,375
Tell you what,
why don't you take Kara and Lauren

1195
01:14:22,500 --> 01:14:26,170
and put them in the box,
and then you and Aaron can each keep a set

1196
01:14:26,295 --> 01:14:28,148
and you'll both have families
and you can stop feeding off it.

1197
01:14:28,172 --> 01:14:30,567
- They'll come back.
- You can each keep a set in a hemisphere.

1198
01:14:30,591 --> 01:14:33,844
And I don't think there's ever been
any reason to show you what I'm capable of

1199
01:14:33,970 --> 01:14:35,471
but I'm telling you this now.

1200
01:14:35,596 --> 01:14:37,682
Go out there
and do whatever the hell you want.

1201
01:14:37,807 --> 01:14:39,934
There's no way in the world
I can stop you.

1202
01:14:40,059 --> 01:14:42,812
But don't come back here,
and don't come near them.

1203
01:14:44,981 --> 01:14:46,357
Any of them.

1204
01:15:01,747 --> 01:15:05,126
<i>(MAN) Now I have repaid any debt
I may have owed you.</i>

1205
01:15:05,251 --> 01:15:07,294
<i>You know all that I know.</i>

1206
01:15:07,420 --> 01:15:10,798
<i>My voice is the only proof
that you will have of the truth of any of this.</i>

1207
01:15:10,923 --> 01:15:13,551
<i>I might have written a letter
with my signature,</i>

1208
01:15:13,676 --> 01:15:15,516
<i>but my handwriting
is not what it used to be.</i>

1209
01:15:15,636 --> 01:15:17,513
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

1210
01:15:18,806 --> 01:15:21,517
<i>Maybe you've had the presence of mind
to record this.</i>

1211
01:15:21,642 --> 01:15:23,102
<i>That's your prerogative.</i>

1212
01:15:23,227 --> 01:15:25,146
<i>You will not be contacted by me again.</i>

1213
01:15:25,271 --> 01:15:26,564
Good morning.

1214
01:15:29,108 --> 01:15:30,484
Every half metre.

1215
01:15:30,609 --> 01:15:32,278
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

1216
01:15:32,403 --> 01:15:33,696
Everywhere.

1217
01:15:34,613 --> 01:15:35,614
Everywhere.

1218
01:15:35,740 --> 01:15:38,159
<i>And if you look, you will not find me.</i>

